** Could you explain the staking/delegating process? With examples, please. **

Delegation allows coldkeys to sign a staking operation onto a hotkey which they do not own, such that the hotkey owner can use those funds for validating within the Bittensor network.

Of the funds emitted to this hotkey, 18% are given to the delegate hotkey itself, then the remainder is distributed between the coldkeys which have delegated stake, in proportion to the amount of stake they delegated respectively.

Example: 
    1. Alice has a coldkey CA and hotkey HA. She nominates HA to become a delegate and stakes 5 tao onto it from her coldkey CA. 

    2. Bob has a coldkey CB and chooses to support Alice by delegating 10 tao to her hotkey HA. 

    3. Alice’s Hotkey HA validates on Finney’s Image network with combined 15 tao, and makes 50 Tao in emission to be distributed onto key HA.

    4. To distribute these funds, the chain takes an initial 18% cut from this 50 Tao (which is 9 Tao) and gives it to HA leaving 41 Tao left over.     

    5. Next the chain distributes the remaining 41 Tao via stake proportions Alice (5/15) and Bob (10/15).  Leaving 5 + 9 + 41 * (5/15) = 27.6 Tao for CA and 10 + 41 * (10/15) = 37.3 Tao for CB. 

    6. In the next mechanism step HA can now use 65 Tao for validating. 
**--------------**
**What about the wallet? We will be able to send/delegate/undelegate TAO directly from the wallet?**
Yes, the Bittensor wallet CLI and web version, once integrated with Finney, will allow delegating stake to validators.
**--------------**
**Do you consider changing the split of daily emission between miners and validators? What will be the split after Finney launch?**
There are no near-term plans to change the emission split between miners and validators.
**--------------**
**Any info about staking period - fixed or variable? Unstaking time?**
We have not yet planned a staking period - fixed or variable. However this is a potential change in Q1.

**--------------**
**When is the rebranding supposed to take place? **
The branding process for Bittensor is a continuous process which includes improvements of the website, our imagery, logo etc. Expect continual improvements to these items through out the year. 

**————**
**If there are only 100 validator spots and a single entity can hold multiple spots, what prevents one (or several) large players from dominating the network?**

Note: 100 validators was an approximation, and not something we have concretely written into  Bittensor.

A single entity could hold more than one slot. However, an attacker seeking N slots must have at least N times the min validator size. Assuming validators are increased in size, and the minimum is 10k Tao, the attacker needs 100k Tao to hold 10 slots and 1 Million Tao to hold all 100. Protection against this attack is thus economic.

**--------------**
**When will you cut number of validators to 100? Will you do a snapshot? Will you inform about the date in advance?**
Stake balances and UIDs will be snapshotted onto Finney. We will provide more concrete numbers closer to the hard launch as to what validator cut-off will be used.

**--------------**
**Will we have an explorer upgrade for user functionality and ease access? No pressure... 😊**
The move to polkadot will come with an improved explorer. However, we hope to stimulate a community built (Bittensor specific explorer) through delegative stake this year.

**--------------**
**How is it possible your team does not have qualitative monitoring of the servers and validators?**
**How will you run the pooled validator if you don’t check the current ones?**

Both of these rhetorical questions refers to the reduced traffic seen on a number of validators over a 3 week period ending with the Finney launch in January. It is important to point out that the Foundation itself is not responsible for these validators, but are instead run by individuals, albeit, closely affiliated with the foundation. We are looking at ways of improving this infrastructure as to ensure this type of outage doesn’t occur in the future and with the introduction of Finney’s delegative staking, likely see the size of individually run validators drastically decrease.

**--------------**
**Any update on the foundation wallet?**
Mid February

**--------------**
**Can we undelegate our TAO whenever we want? If yes, how?**
Yes you can, through the btcli unstake command and soon through btcli undelegate.

**--------------**
**Will we have a full list of possible cli commands; full list, not the basics?**
To view the full list you can run btcli —help

**--------------**
**Can apps on other AI block chains such as FET and AGIX tap into the Bittensor network?**
Not that we are aware.

**--------------**
**When does delegating stake to validators go live? any concrete dates? Tao Rules!**
The same day that we launch Finney onto Polkadot (Q1)

**--------------**
**After the launch of Finney there will be only 100 validators. What will happen in case that one of of the Validator will underperform? Will you take next one?**

Validators will be forced to compete with other validators by providing services for the Bittensor community AND importantly by ensuring that dividends are high as to attract delegated stake. If a validator underperforms they will lose those funds.

**--------------**
**When will the block explorer be released?**
We are not actively building an explorer and hope that we can stimulate the community to build one.

**--------------**
**How can a newbie become a competitive miner? Currently, existing miners with their proprietary fine-tuned models hinder newcomers.**
Ask questions, don’t lose heart, and eventually you will make it. Finney will open up new networks with more slots making the onramp easier for newcomers.

**--------------**
**There is nothing stopping validators redistributing a % of the fee (18%) to holders and thus undercutting your set fee. Will you relook at this fee structure?**
We expect this to happen, and we imagine that many people will attempt to circumnavigate the 18%. However, for those seeking to drive innovation in Bittensor, the 18% flat rate centres the delegated stake competition around *provided value* rather than *reduced fees*. This was designed to stimulate competition from validator (teams) to build things which drive total community value, for instance, by building an explorer. For those seeking simply to maximize personal return, there will be alternatives built by many.

**--------------**
**Could you explain the delegation numbers again? Is it 18% of 33% reward?**
18% is the amount initial taken by the delegate before the remaining 82% are distributed based on stake proportion.
